   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Background"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e687594b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In Zero Noise Extrapolation (`ZNE`), expectation value of an algorithm (quantum circuit) is computed at multiple noise levels. Next, the expectation values are fitted using a choice of fitting function such as linear, quadratic, and exponential to extrapolate the expectation value in the zero noise limit.\n",
    "\n",
    "To amplify the noise in the quantum circuit, usually two methods are followed: (1) pulse stretching and (2) digital ZNE (Giurgica-Tiron et al., https://arxiv.org/abs/2005.10921). In the pulse stretching variant, to a first order, the durations of gate pulses in a circuit are extended by a constant factor while the amplitude is appropriately lowered such that pulse still achieves the same logical function. However, due to extended gate duration, the circuit will now undergo more noise.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the digital ZNE, gates in a circuit are repeated such that the logical function of the cirucit remains intact. For example, the inverse of CNOT gate is a CNOT. Thus, if a CNOT is repeated three times, it will still behave as a CNOT. However, due to elevated gate counts, now the circuit will experience more noise. Repeating a gate while keeping its logical function intact is often referred to as **\"gate folding\"** in ZNE literature.\n",
    "\n",
    "In this notebook, we will follow the digital variant of ZNE and demonstrate how to transform a quantum circuit to increase its gate count to amplify the noise while keeping the logical function same."
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b4d6e902",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "![analog_vs_digital.png](imgs/analog_vs_digital.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a18e09d7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "![global_vs_local.png](imgs/global_vs_local.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "210ed55b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Each method has its pros and cons:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Analog stretching\n",
    "    - Formally correct method\n",
    "    - Can stretch to arbitrary scaling factors\n",
    "    - Requires calibration of gates for all sretch factors\n",
    "    - Harder to implement without direct hardware access\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- Digital stretching\n",
    "    - Much easier to implement\n",
    "    - Not directly the same as analog stretch\n",
    "    - No additional calibrations required\n",
    "    - Stuck with stretch factors of 1,3,5,... (to some extent)\n",
    "    - Can easily hit T1 limit on deeper circuits"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "783904af",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Imports"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "eaaf56b9",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "\n",
    "from qiskit import QuantumCircuit, transpile\n",
    "from qiskit.circuit import QuantumRegister\n",
    "from qiskit.providers.fake_provider import FakeMumbai\n",
    "from qiskit.quantum_info import SparsePauliOp\n",
    "from qiskit.result import sampled_expectation_value\n",
    "\n",
    "# Classes for building up a directed-acyclic graph (DAG) structure\n",
    "from qiskit.dagcircuit import DAGCircuit\n",
    "# Transpiler stuff neded to make a pass and passmanager\n",
    "from qiskit.transpiler import PassManager\n",
    "from qiskit.transpiler.basepasses import TransformationPass\n",
    "\n",
    "# A fake system to transpile against\n",
    "from qiskit.providers.fake_provider import FakeHanoiV2\n",
    "\n",
    "from qiskit_aer import AerSimulator"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "674991a1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Setup: test circuit and backend"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "6a0d7451",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Create Circuit\n",
    "def create_ghz_circuit(num_qubits):\n",
    "    ghz_circuit = QuantumCircuit(num_qubits, num_qubits)\n",
    "    ghz_circuit.h(0)\n",
    "    for qubit in range(1, num_qubits):\n",
    "        ghz_circuit.cx(0, qubit)\n",
    "\n",
    "    ghz_circuit.barrier()\n",
    "    ghz_circuit.measure(range(num_qubits), range(num_qubits))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    return ghz_circuit"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "db1bd61c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "num_qubits = 5\n",
    "circuit = create_ghz_circuit(num_qubits=num_qubits)\n",
    "operator = SparsePauliOp(\"Z\"*num_qubits)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "129c805a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "ideal_simulator = AerSimulator()\n",
    "backend = FakeMumbai()\n",
    "transpiled_circuit = transpile(circuit, backend=backend, optimization_level=3)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "0c7da0a0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1528.96x535.111 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 5,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "transpiled_circuit.draw(\"mpl\", idle_wires=False)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d2812833",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# ZNE Circuit Transformation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "b015ebd1",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Local2qFolding(TransformationPass):\n",
    "    \"\"\"A circuit transformation pass to create noise-amplified version of a circuit\\\n",
    "    by folding 2-qubit gates in the circuit.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    The pass identifies the gate (op) nodes of the specified 2-qubit gate (`self.folding_gate`)\n",
    "    and replace the node with a folded version of the gate (G) such as `G*G^-1*G`,\n",
    "    `G*G^-1*G*G^-1*G`, and so on.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    In IBM systems, the available 2q gates are CX, ECR, and CZ, and each of them\n",
    "    is inverse of its own (i.e., the inverese of ECR is ECR itself). Thus, repeating an IBM 2q gate an odd integer\n",
    "    numer of times folds the gate (increases gate counts or noise but keepe the logical functionality intact).\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    def __init__(self, scale_factor, folding_gate):\n",
    "        super().__init__()\n",
    "        self.scale_factor = scale_factor\n",
    "        self.folding_gate = folding_gate\n",
    "        \n",
    "    def run(self, dag):\n",
    "        for run in dag.collect_runs([self.folding_gate]):\n",
    "            for node in run: # iterates over all op nodes of self.folding_gate\n",
    "                # create an empty DAG that will replace the op node\n",
    "                fold_dag = DAGCircuit()\n",
    "\n",
    "                # Add a register of qubits (here always 2Q)\n",
    "                qreg = QuantumRegister(2)\n",
    "                fold_dag.add_qreg(qreg)\n",
    "                \n",
    "                # adding the 2q gate an odd number of times in the DAG\n",
    "                for _ in range(self.scale_factor):\n",
    "                    fold_dag.apply_operation_back(node.op, [qreg[0], qreg[1]])\n",
    "                \n",
    "                # Replace the op node in the original DAG\n",
    "                dag.substitute_node_with_dag(node, fold_dag)\n",
    "                \n",
    "        return dag   "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "3646045f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1708.89x535.111 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 7,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Using the ZNE circuit transformation pass\n",
    "# scale_factor=3 --> the 2q gate (CX) is supposed to be repeated 3 times\n",
    "pm = PassManager([Local2qFolding(scale_factor=3, folding_gate='cx')])\n",
    "circuit3x = pm.run(circuit)\n",
    "circuit3x.draw(\"mpl\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "66dcd6ad",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2228.78x1120.39 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 8,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "transpiled_circuit3x = pm.run(transpiled_circuit)\n",
    "transpiled_circuit3x.draw(\"mpl\", idle_wires=False)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "337a5ed8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2228.78x1120.39 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 9,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# scale_factor=5 --> the 2q gate (CX) is supposed to be repeated 5 times\n",
    "pm = PassManager([Local2qFolding(scale_factor=5, folding_gate='cx')])\n",
    "transpiled_circuit5x = pm.run(transpiled_circuit)\n",
    "transpiled_circuit5x.draw(\"mpl\", idle_wires=False)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "092e4e62",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Circuit Execution"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "id": "4f5f86a1",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# ideal simulation\n",
    "ideal_counts = ideal_simulator.run(transpiled_circuit, shots=10000).result().get_counts()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "4d39d5d8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Convert Counts to expectation value\n",
    "ideal_expval = sampled_expectation_value(dist=ideal_counts, oper=operator)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "id": "4bca7bad",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "zne_circ_list = [transpiled_circuit, transpiled_circuit3x, transpiled_circuit5x]\n",
    "noisy_counts = backend.run(zne_circ_list, shots=10000).result().get_counts()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "id": "fbc0b4c3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Convert Counts to expectation value as ZNE works on expectation value only\n",
    "noisy_expvals = [sampled_expectation_value(dist=dist, oper=operator) for dist in noisy_counts]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9fd0c972",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Post-processing"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "id": "d4f1aea7",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Now, we will fit the expectation values to extrapolate into zero noise limit\n",
    "# using numpy.polyfit\n",
    "# x values --> noise scale factors, i.e., [1, 3, 5]\n",
    "# y values --> expectation values at each noise level\n",
    "# linear fit\n",
    "p = np.polyfit(x=[1, 3, 5], y=noisy_expvals, deg=1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "id": "483957d8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "zero_noise_limit = np.polyval(p, x=0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "id": "a20d3dee",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "ideal expectation value: 0.0036\n",
      "noisy expectation value: 0.058\n",
      "mitigated expecation value (zne): 0.049333333333333326 \n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(f\"ideal expectation value: {ideal_expval}\")\n",
    "print(f\"noisy expectation value: {noisy_expvals[0]}\")\n",
    "print(f\"mitigated expecation value (zne): {zero_noise_limit} \")"
   ]
  },
